---
import ToolLayout from '../../layouts/ToolLayout.astro';

const title = 'Hours Calculator';
const description =
  'Free hours calculator. Work out the hours and minutes between two times, with an optional break deducted, shown as decimal hours too.';
const intro =
  'Enter a start and end time (and any break) to see the total hours and minutes worked — also shown as decimal hours.';
const category = { id: 'everyday', name: 'Everyday' };
const faqs = [
  { q: 'Does it handle overnight shifts?', a: 'Yes. If the end time is earlier than the start time, it assumes the shift runs past midnight and adds 24 hours.' },
  { q: 'What are decimal hours?', a: 'Decimal hours express minutes as a fraction of an hour (e.g. 8 hours 30 minutes = 8.5 hours), which is how many payroll systems calculate pay.' },
  { q: 'Can I subtract a break?', a: 'Yes — enter your break in minutes and it is removed from the total.' },
  { q: 'What if I work a split shift?', a: 'Calculate each segment separately using the same tool and add the results. For example, a morning shift of 4 hours and an evening shift of 3 hours.' },
  { q: 'How do decimal hours compare to hh:mm?', a: 'Decimal hours express minutes as a fraction of an hour. For example, 8 hours 30 minutes = 8.5 hours. This format is what most payroll systems use for calculating pay.' },
  { q: 'Can I calculate pay from hours worked?', a: 'Not directly — but once you have the decimal hours, multiply by your hourly rate to get gross pay. For example, 8.5 hours x $20/hour = $170.' },
  { q: 'What is the standard work day duration?', a: 'Most full-time employees work 7.5–8 hours per day (excluding lunch break). Part-time schedules vary widely from 3–6 hours daily.' },
  { q: 'How do I calculate overtime?', a: 'Calculate total hours worked, then subtract the standard hours for your role (typically 8 hours/day or 40 hours/week). The remainder is overtime.' },
];
---

<ToolLayout title={title} description={description} intro={intro} category={category} faqs={faqs}>
  <div class="mt-6 rounded-2xl border border-slate-200 bg-white p-4 shadow-sm sm:p-6">
    <div class="grid gap-4 sm:grid-cols-3">
      <label class="block"><span class="text-sm font-medium text-slate-700">Start time</span>
        <input id="start" type="time" value="09:00" class="mt-1 w-full rounded-xl border border-slate-300 p-3 outline-none focus:border-indigo-400 focus:ring-2 focus:ring-indigo-100" /></label>
      <label class="block"><span class="text-sm font-medium text-slate-700">End time</span>
        <input id="end" type="time" value="17:30" class="mt-1 w-full rounded-xl border border-slate-300 p-3 outline-none focus:border-indigo-400 focus:ring-2 focus:ring-indigo-100" /></label>
      <label class="block"><span class="text-sm font-medium text-slate-700">Break (minutes)</span>
        <input id="brk" type="number" step="1" value="30" class="mt-1 w-full rounded-xl border border-slate-300 p-3 outline-none focus:border-indigo-400 focus:ring-2 focus:ring-indigo-100" /></label>
    </div>
    <div class="mt-6 grid grid-cols-1 gap-3 sm:grid-cols-2">
      <div class="rounded-xl bg-indigo-600 p-5 text-center text-white"><div class="text-sm opacity-80">Total time</div><div id="r-hm" class="mt-1 text-2xl font-bold">—</div></div>
      <div class="rounded-xl bg-slate-50 p-5 text-center"><div class="text-sm text-slate-500">Decimal hours</div><div id="r-dec" class="mt-1 text-2xl font-bold text-slate-800">—</div></div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <section class="mt-10">
    <h2 class="text-xl font-bold text-slate-900">How hours calculation works</h2>
    <p class="mt-2 text-slate-600">
      The hours calculator converts start and end times into total minutes since midnight, subtracts break time, then formats the result. First, both times are converted: <code>totalMinutes = hours × 60 + minutes</code>. The difference is computed as <code>endMinutes - startMinutes</code>. If the result is negative (overnight shift), 24 hours (1,440 minutes) are added.
    </p>
    <p class="mt-3 text-slate-600">
      For decimal hours (used by payroll systems), the total minutes are divided by 60: <code>decimalHours = totalMinutes ÷ 60</code>. This expresses 8 hours 30 minutes as 8.50 hours. To calculate gross pay, multiply decimal hours by your hourly rate: 8.50 × $25 = $212.50.
    </p>
    <div class="mt-5 rounded-xl border border-slate-200 bg-slate-50 p-5">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-slate-900">Worked examples</h3>
      <div class="mt-2 grid gap-2 text-sm sm:grid-cols-2">
        <div><span class="font-medium text-slate-700">Standard shift:</span> <span class="text-slate-600">09:00–17:30, 30 min break = <strong>8h 0m (8.00 h)</strong></span></div>
        <div><span class="font-medium text-slate-700">Overnight:</span> <span class="text-slate-600">22:00–06:00, 0 min break = <strong>8h 0m (8.00 h)</strong></span></div>
        <div><span class="font-medium text-slate-700">With overtime:</span> <span class="text-slate-600">08:00–18:15, 45 min break = <strong>9h 30m (9.50 h)</strong></span></div>
        <div><span class="font-medium text-slate-700">Pay calculation:</span> <span class="text-slate-600">8.00 h × $18.50/hr = <strong>$148.00 gross</strong></span></div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <figure class="mt-10">
    <svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" viewBox="0 0 800 200" width="800" height="200" role="img" aria-labelledby="hrs-title hrs-desc">
      <title id="hrs-title">Work Shift Timeline Diagram</title>
      <desc id="hrs-desc">A horizontal timeline showing start time, work period, break, work period, and end time for a typical work shift</desc>
      <rect x="50" y="50" width="280" height="36" rx="6" fill="#c7d2fe" />
      <rect x="50" y="50" width="140" height="36" rx="6" fill="#6366f1" />
      <text x="120" y="73" text-anchor="middle" fill="#fff" font-family="system-ui, sans-serif" font-size="13" font-weight="600">Work</text>

      <rect x="330" y="50" width="60" height="36" rx="6" fill="#fde68a" />
      <text x="360" y="73" text-anchor="middle" fill="#92400e" font-family="system-ui, sans-serif" font-size="12" font-weight="600">Break</text>

      <rect x="390" y="50" width="210" height="36" rx="6" fill="#a5b4fc" />
      <rect x="390" y="50" width="140" height="36" rx="6" fill="#818cf8" />
      <text x="460" y="73" text-anchor="middle" fill="#fff" font-family="system-ui, sans-serif" font-size="13" font-weight="600">Work</text>

      <line x1="50" y1="110" x2="750" y2="110" stroke="#cbd5e1" stroke-width="2" />
      <circle cx="50" cy="110" r="5" fill="#6366f1" />
      <circle cx="750" cy="110" r="5" fill="#6366f1" />
      <text x="50" y="135" fill="#475569" font-family="system-ui, sans-serif" font-size="12" font-weight="600">09:00</text>
      <text x="189" y="135" text-anchor="middle" fill="#64748b" font-family="system-ui, sans-serif" font-size="11">Start</text>
      <text x="360" y="135" text-anchor="middle" fill="#64748b" font-family="system-ui, sans-serif" font-size="11">30 min</text>
      <text x="750" y="135" text-anchor="end" fill="#475569" font-family="system-ui, sans-serif" font-size="12" font-weight="600">17:30</text>

      <line x1="330" y1="92" x2="330" y2="110" stroke="#94a3b8" stroke-width="1" stroke-dasharray="3" />
      <line x1="390" y1="92" x2="390" y2="110" stroke="#94a3b8" stroke-width="1" stroke-dasharray="3" />

      <rect x="610" y="48" width="140" height="40" rx="6" fill="#4338ca" />
      <text x="680" y="73" text-anchor="middle" fill="#fff" font-family="system-ui, sans-serif" font-size="14" font-weight="700">Total: 8h 0m</text>

      <text x="400" y="170" text-anchor="middle" fill="#64748b" font-family="system-ui, sans-serif" font-size="12">Start and end times define the shift; break time is subtracted for the final total</text>
    </svg>
    <figcaption class="mt-2 text-center text-sm text-slate-500">A typical work shift: start time, work periods, break, and end time combine to show total hours</figcaption>
  </figure>

  <section class="mt-10">
    <h2 class="text-xl font-bold text-slate-900">Why tracking hours matters</h2>
    <p class="mt-2 text-slate-600">
      Whether you are an employee filling in a timesheet, a freelancer billing by the hour, or a manager approving payroll, accurate hour tracking is essential. A few minutes of error per day adds up to hours per month — and real money. This calculator makes it easy to get precise totals including break deductions and overnight shifts.
    </p>

    <div class="mt-5 space-y-3">
      <div>
        <div class="flex items-baseline justify-between text-sm"><span class="font-medium text-slate-700">Standard full-time shift</span><span class="text-slate-400">7.5–8 hours</span></div>
        <div class="mt-1 h-3 w-full rounded-full bg-slate-100"><div class="h-3 rounded-full bg-indigo-500" style="width:32%"></div></div>
      </div>
      <div>
        <div class="flex items-baseline justify-between text-sm"><span class="font-medium text-slate-700">Part-time shift</span><span class="text-slate-400">4–6 hours</span></div>
        <div class="mt-1 h-3 w-full rounded-full bg-slate-100"><div class="h-3 rounded-full bg-indigo-500" style="width:24%"></div></div>
      </div>
      <div>
        <div class="flex items-baseline justify-between text-sm"><span class="font-medium text-slate-700">Freelance daily billable</span><span class="text-slate-400">5–7 hours</span></div>
        <div class="mt-1 h-3 w-full rounded-full bg-slate-100"><div class="h-3 rounded-full bg-emerald-500" style="width:28%"></div></div>
      </div>
      <div>
        <div class="flex items-baseline justify-between text-sm"><span class="font-medium text-slate-700">Double shift</span><span class="text-slate-400">12–16 hours</span></div>
        <div class="mt-1 h-3 w-full rounded-full bg-slate-100"><div class="h-3 rounded-full bg-emerald-500" style="width:64%"></div></div>
      </div>
      <div>
        <div class="flex items-baseline justify-between text-sm"><span class="font-medium text-slate-700">Overnight / graveyard</span><span class="text-slate-400">8–12 hours (past midnight)</span></div>
        <div class="mt-1 h-3 w-full rounded-full bg-slate-100"><div class="h-3 rounded-full bg-violet-500" style="width:48%"></div></div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="mt-10 grid gap-4 sm:grid-cols-2">
    <div class="rounded-xl border border-slate-200 bg-white p-5">
      <span class="text-2xl">💼</span>
      <h3 class="mt-2 font-semibold text-slate-900">Employees</h3>
      <p class="mt-1 text-sm text-slate-600">Fill in timesheets accurately. Track clock-in and clock-out times including unpaid breaks. Know your exact hours before payday.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="rounded-xl border border-slate-200 bg-white p-5">
      <span class="text-2xl">💻</span>
      <h3 class="mt-2 font-semibold text-slate-900">Freelancers</h3>
      <p class="mt-1 text-sm text-slate-600">Track billable hours per client. The decimal-hours display matches what invoicing platforms expect — no manual conversion needed.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="rounded-xl border border-slate-200 bg-white p-5">
      <span class="text-2xl">👔</span>
      <h3 class="mt-2 font-semibold text-slate-900">Managers</h3>
      <p class="mt-1 text-sm text-slate-600">Verify team timesheets, approve payroll hours, and check for overtime. Quickly spot discrepancies between reported and expected hours.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="rounded-xl border border-slate-200 bg-white p-5">
      <span class="text-2xl">📋</span>
      <h3 class="mt-2 font-semibold text-slate-900">HR & Payroll</h3>
      <p class="mt-1 text-sm text-slate-600">Process timesheets efficiently. Decimal hours (e.g. 37.50) integrate directly with most payroll software without reformatting.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="mt-10">
    <h2 class="text-xl font-bold text-slate-900">How to use the hours calculator</h2>
    <div class="mt-4 grid gap-4 sm:grid-cols-3">
      <div class="rounded-xl border border-slate-200 bg-white p-4 text-center">
        <span class="inline-flex h-10 w-10 items-center justify-center rounded-full bg-indigo-100 text-lg font-bold text-indigo-700">1</span>
        <h3 class="mt-3 font-semibold text-slate-900">Enter start & end</h3>
        <p class="mt-1 text-sm text-slate-600">Use the time pickers for clock-in and clock-out times. Overnight shifts are handled automatically.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="rounded-xl border border-slate-200 bg-white p-4 text-center">
        <span class="inline-flex h-10 w-10 items-center justify-center rounded-full bg-indigo-100 text-lg font-bold text-indigo-700">2</span>
        <h3 class="mt-3 font-semibold text-slate-900">Add break time</h3>
        <p class="mt-1 text-sm text-slate-600">Enter unpaid break duration in minutes. Set to 0 if no break is taken.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="rounded-xl border border-slate-200 bg-white p-4 text-center">
        <span class="inline-flex h-10 w-10 items-center justify-center rounded-full bg-indigo-100 text-lg font-bold text-indigo-700">3</span>
        <h3 class="mt-3 font-semibold text-slate-900">See both formats</h3>
        <p class="mt-1 text-sm text-slate-600">View total in hh:mm format plus decimal hours for payroll integration.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="mt-10 rounded-2xl border border-slate-200 bg-white p-6">
    <h2 class="text-xl font-bold text-slate-900">Smart time tracking tips</h2>
    <div class="mt-4 space-y-5">
      <div>
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-slate-900">Track in real time</h3>
        <p class="mt-1 text-sm text-slate-600">Log your hours daily rather than estimating at the end of the week. Small rounding errors compound — 5 minutes a day is over 20 hours a year.</p>
      </div>
      <div>
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-slate-900">Know your break policy</h3>
        <p class="mt-1 text-sm text-slate-600">Most jurisdictions require unpaid breaks for shifts over 5–6 hours. Check your local labor laws and subtract accordingly for accurate timesheets.</p>
      </div>
      <div>
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-slate-900">Convert to pay easily</h3>
        <p class="mt-1 text-sm text-slate-600">Multiply decimal hours by your hourly rate to get gross pay before tax. Example: 8.5 hours x $25/hour = $212.50 for the day.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="mt-10">
    <h2 class="text-xl font-bold text-slate-900">When to use the hours calculator</h2>
    <p class="mt-2 text-slate-600">
      The hours calculator is essential for anyone who needs to track work time accurately, whether as an employee filling out a weekly timesheet, a freelancer billing clients by the hour, or a manager approving payroll. Employees use it to verify their clock-in and clock-out times match their pay stubs, ensuring they are paid for every minute worked. Freelancers and contractors rely on it to produce accurate invoices that reflect their exact billable hours, including break deductions. The decimal hours output is particularly valuable because it matches the format used by most payroll and invoicing platforms, eliminating manual conversion errors.
    </p>
    <p class="mt-3 text-slate-600">
      Another important use case is calculating overtime and shift differentials. A worker who clocks in at 8:00 AM and leaves at 6:15 PM with a 45-minute unpaid break has worked 9 hours and 30 minutes. If their standard day is 8 hours, the overtime is 1 hour and 30 minutes. The calculator handles overnight shifts automatically, making it ideal for night-shift workers in healthcare, manufacturing, hospitality, and security. HR professionals use it to audit timesheets, ensuring break policies are followed and overtime is calculated correctly according to labor regulations.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="mt-10">
    <h2 class="text-xl font-bold text-slate-900">Limitations and considerations</h2>
    <p class="mt-2 text-slate-600">
      While the hours calculator is accurate for straightforward time tracking, there are important limitations to keep in mind. It does not support split shifts, where an employee works two separate blocks in a single day (for example, 6 AM to 10 AM and then 4 PM to 8 PM). For such schedules, you must calculate each segment separately and add the results together manually. The tool also does not handle rounding policies that some companies use, such as rounding to the nearest quarter-hour. If your employer rounds clock-in times to the nearest 15 minutes as a standard practice, you need to apply that rounding yourself before entering the times.
    </p>
    <p class="mt-3 text-slate-600">
      Another consideration is that the calculator treats all minutes equally regardless of when the break occurs. Labor laws in some jurisdictions require breaks at specific intervals, such as a 30-minute break after 5 consecutive hours of work. The calculator does not validate compliance with these regulations; it simply subtracts the total break minutes you enter. For accurate record-keeping, especially in contexts subject to audit or legal review, you should maintain a separate log of actual break times rather than entering an estimated daily average. Finally, the tool assumes a single continuous work period for each calculation, so multiple disjoint sessions must be computed separately.
    </p>
  </section>

  <script is:inline>
    const el = (id) => document.getElementById(id);
    function update() {
      const s = el('start').value, e = el('end').value;
      if (!s || !e) { el('r-hm').textContent = el('r-dec').textContent = '—'; return; }
      const [sh, sm] = s.split(':').map(Number), [eh, em] = e.split(':').map(Number);
      let mins = (eh * 60 + em) - (sh * 60 + sm);
      if (mins < 0) mins += 24 * 60;
      mins -= parseInt(el('brk').value, 10) || 0;
      if (mins < 0) mins = 0;
      const h = Math.floor(mins / 60), m = mins % 60;
      el('r-hm').textContent = `${h}h ${m}m`;
      el('r-dec').textContent = (mins / 60).toFixed(2) + ' h';
    }
    ['start', 'end', 'brk'].forEach((id) => el(id).addEventListener('input', update));
    update();
  </script>
</ToolLayout>
